# Keep SPEC.md Updated

Whenever you make a change that affects what the user can see or do — a new feature, a changed behavior, a removed feature, or a changed flow — you **must** update `SPEC.md` in the same response.

## What triggers an update

- Adding or removing a screen or route
- Adding or removing a user-visible action (button, menu item, gesture, etc.)
- Changing how a flow works (e.g., save behavior, navigation, confirmation dialogs)
- Adding or removing a display mode, filter, or sort option
- Changes to what data is shown on any screen
- Adding or removing offline/PWA behavior
- Moving a feature from "Planned" to "Implemented" (or vice versa)

## What does NOT trigger an update

- Internal refactors with no user-facing change
- Performance improvements
- Bug fixes that restore already-documented behavior
- Style or CSS changes
- Test changes

## How to update SPEC.md

- Edit only the relevant section(s). Do not rewrite the whole file.
- Keep the language user-facing: describe what the user experiences, not how it is implemented.
- If a feature moves from planned to done, move the bullet from "Planned" to "Implemented" in the Status section. Remove it from Planned entirely — do not keep it in both places.
- If you add a genuinely new feature not mentioned anywhere, add it to the appropriate section.
- Do not add implementation details, technology names, or code references to SPEC.md.
- Do not record design history, rejected alternatives, or bug fixes. See `documentation.mdc` for the full doc policy.
